  "text": "Once break-out groups had identified broad protection goals they considered relevant for environmental risk assessment, they were asked to construct potential 'pathways to harm' . This is a general tool that helps identify and characterize the ways a particular 'action' (in this case the introduction of gene drive mosquitoes) might lead to harmful effects on the broad protection goals [CITATION_1] . It requires first the refinement of a broad protection goal into a more operational goal, and then the identification of measurable endpoints that could be used to assess harm. The pathway is then constructed in as much detail as possible to identify all the events that must occur between the action and a potential harm. By doing this, it is possible to better identify whether a suggested harm is actually plausible, and if it is, to identify the types of information that will be useful in assessing the likelihood of the harm being realized, and if warranted, plan potential mitigation strategies.",
